        <body>       
                                

                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Rev. Dr S. Morais<lb/>
                5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St near Green St<lb/>
                Philadelphia<lb/></p>
            <p>From<lb/>
                1607 Diamond St.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>1607 Diamond St.<lb/>
                Philadelphia<lb/>
                Sept. 13<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1893<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Dr Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>I have enclosed a couple of<lb/> clippings from a London paper that<lb/> may prove of interest to you.<lb/></p>
            <p>The epitaph is certainly ingenious<lb/> as well as original&#44; &#38; the other cutting<lb/> tells us a delightful bit of news<lb/> about the old sacred building.<lb/></p>
            <p>The <sic>conflagation</sic> referred to destroyed<lb/> a great deal of property on St. Mary<lb/> Ave.&#44; Bury St &#38; Bevis Marks.<lb/>
                With kindest regards &#38; best wishes for &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> from<lb/> Yrs. sincerely<lb/> J. Leonard Levy.<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                Ah&#33; l&#39;uom	&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                misero &#232;&#44;	&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                se notte&#44; e di&#44;	&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                pene&#44; e lai&#44;	&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                oime&#33;		&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                suol cibar	&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                Chi nasce muor&#59;&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                Animati&#44;	&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                a voi giammai	&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                avvenga mal&#59;	&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>
                ah&#33; che passo&#33;	&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>The ancient place of worship of the Spanish and Portuguese Synagogue<lb/> in Bevis Marks had last week&#44; owing to the great conflagration in<lb/> its immediate vicinity&#44; a very narrow escape from destruction by fire&#44; and<lb/> that close upon the anniversary of the loss of the Second Temple.  The<lb/> construction of the present Portuguese Synagogue was commenced in 1699<lb/> on a plot of land for which a lease was obtained from the owners&#44; Sir Thomas<lb/> and Lady Ann Pointz.  Subsequently this leasehold was converted into a<lb/> freehold.  The new synagogue was consecrated in 1702&#44; and it is curious to<lb/> recollect that at that time the Jews received several proofs of friendship from<lb/> Christians.  In the first place&#44; it is related that the reigning sovereign&#44;<lb/> Queen Anne&#44; presented the Jews with a beam&#44; which is still found on the<lb/> roof of the Bevis Marks Synagogue.  It is also recorded that the builder&#44; a<lb/> too scrupulous Quaker&#44; returned to the Sephardic authorities a sum equal<lb/> to the profits he would realize under the contract.  He would not retain for<lb/> his own use any of the coin intended for the erection of a Temple of God.<lb/></p>
            </body>
